	 <p style="font-size:25px;text-align:center"><strong> What to Bring: </strong></p>

	<div class="well">
		<p style="font-size:15px;text-align:center;">
		<strong>Navigation:</strong><br>
		Always pack a <b>compass</b> and multiple copies of a <b>topographic map</b> of your hike. GPS navigators, such as the Gaia GPS app for iPhone, can make navigation easier.<br>
		<strong>Sun Protection:</strong><br>
		<b>Sunglasses</b> with 100% UV protection are crucial to backpacking.  <b>Sunscreen</b> is also necessary. Make sure to choose a brand that has an SPF of at least 30, blocks UVA and UVB rays, and ideally has an active ingredient of zinc oxide- try to avoid oxybenzone or avobenzone. For trips that include prolonged stretches of ice or snow, we recommend glacier glasses, sun-protected clothing and buffs, and SPF lip balm.<br>
		<strong>Insulation:</strong><br>
		<b>Layers!</b> Besides your regular hiking clothes- non-cotton short sleeve shirt, shorts, or pants- layers for unpredictable weather conditions are needed. This means fleece long underwear, insulated midlayer, waterproof pants, waterproof shell, insulated wool hat, and extra wool socks.<br>
		<strong>Nutrition:</strong><br>
		Pack at least an extra day's worth of <b>food</b>. This can include snacks such as salami, nuts, and energy bars or cook items, such as freeze dried meals or oatmeal.<br>
		<strong>Hydration:</strong><br>
		Always pack water <b>bottles</b> and/or <b>reservoirs</b> with around 3 liters in capacity, along with multiple forms of <b>water filtration</b>. These can include squeeze filters, gravity filters, water purification tablets, or UV filters.<br>
		<strong>Fire:</strong><br>
		<b>Waterproof matches</b> are essential to backpacking, and are used for lighting your <b>stove</b> or fire in the morning and night. We recommend backpacking stoves of the gas canister variety because they are small and portable. if your stove breaks, <b>firestarter</b> is necessary as well. Dry tinder in a waterproof bag, magnesium, priming paste, paraffin, or even lint all suffice.<br>
		<strong>Illumination:</strong><br>
		We recommend two forms of illumination: a <b>headlamp</b> and a small <b>flashlight</b>, along with extra batteries. <br>
		<strong>First Aid:</strong><br>
		We recommend packing pre-assembled <b>first aid kits</b>, as sized by the length of your trip and number of people accompanying you. Always bring extra moleskin for blisters, bandaids, gauze, adhesive tape, disinfecting wipes, and pain medication.<br>
		<strong>Shelter:</strong><br>
		For overnight trips, always pack a <b>tent</b>, as determined by your party size, and/or a <b>tarp</b> for sleeping outdoors. <b>Emergency shelter</b> supplies are also necessary: 50 ft cord and ultralight tarp, bivy sack, or emergency space blanket are options for protection from unfortunate weather conditions.<br>
		<strong>Repair Tools:</strong><br>
		Always pack a <b>knife</b> or a <b>multitool</b>, which are useful for food preparation, gear repair, defense, and first aid. <b>Duct tape</b> is also necessary, and be helpful for repairing sleeping pads, backpacks, jackets, etc.
